{"summary":"Accept fr-13-36f0aa72 and fr-13-a74a46a6 as concrete correctness/idempotency fixes. Reject fr-13-ca8af530 because it would undo intentional legacy collapse/backfill behavior, and reject fr-13-8f43b7ad because it points at a timestamp-model limitation but proposes only test/documentation rather than a concrete correctness remedy.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-13-ca8af530","decision":"reject","rationale":"The fallback from a named terminal row to a unique open legacy group is consistent with the existing legacy-compatibility model: when a start row has no run_id, attempt identity is intentionally recovered from bead_id + project_id + started_at, and existing tests already codify that a later named terminal can merge into that legacy start. Adding an entry.run_id.is_none() guard would break that backfill/dedup path and leave replayed or repaired legacy completions split into duplicate attempts."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-8f43b7ad","decision":"reject","rationale":"This identifies a limitation of using started_at as the ordering key, but the proposed amendment does not supply a correctness fix. If a stale row carries a later started_at because of clock skew, the current model has no trustworthy signal that a different row is actually newer; a test would only codify existing behavior, and documentation alone does not make the ordering more robust. A real fix would require an additional causal ordering signal, not just more test coverage."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-36f0aa72","decision":"accept","rationale":"compare_task_run_recency currently compares finished_at before any tie-break that distinguishes attempts with the same started_at, so an earlier terminal attempt can outrank a later retry that is still running. Because the codebase already preserves same-timestamp distinct retries, this is a real snapshot bug: reconcile_snapshot_from_lineage can report no active bead and zero in-progress work while a retry is active. The recency logic needs a deterministic same-timestamp rule plus a regression test."},{"amendment_id":"fr-13-a74a46a6","decision":"accept","rationale":"The partial-write recovery gap is real. record_bead_start persists lineage/snapshot before appending the BeadStarted journal event, so a journal failure can leave a running row behind. Named retries recover because run_id matching reuses that row, but runless retries only recover when the caller repeats the exact original started_at; otherwise record_task_run_start falls into the already-active error path and strands the partial write. Widening the runless reuse/backfill path for the single matching running attempt is a sound idempotency fix and should be regression-tested."}]}